description:
Free from limbo and once again on her own in the realm of Myst, Sela is desperate to find a way back to earth and save her daughter from the Dark One's evil designs. Her quest to find her way home leads her deep into the heart of a forbidden part of Myst...to a place where it is said that no one has ever returned from...a place known only as the Tomb of Death.

description: On the banks of the Nile, in an ancient Egyptian shrine, some unlucky tourists find a horrible death. Their bloodless corpses lie in front of a ancient and ruined statue, that undoubtedly depicted Bastet, the cat-goddess. Harlan and friends, who came to Egypt to face the she-vampire, meet some old acquaintances and stumble upon a dangerous secret, able to overturn the dusky life of the undead...
name: Il ritorno di Bastet

description: From the bottom of Grado lagoon, an old stringed instrument resurfaced: it's a psaltery, that once belonged to the famous musician, Giorgio Mainerio, notorious for being charged of witchcraft several centuries ago. Father Alvise believes the instrument to be the terrible “psaltheryum diaboli” and asks Harlan and friends for help. Though lying for a very long time underwater, the psaltery is in pristine condition. But playing it can be very dangerous...

description: Without heeding the negative advice of the local Maori, and notwithstanding the strange disappearance of some trekkers, a TV crew enters the forests of New Zealand to film an adventure-themed “reality show”. Unforeseen events will change their adventure in an horror film: in the lonely wildness of the Catlins somebody found the ancient flute of the Patu-paiarehe, and the diabolical shepherd evoked his flock, the fearful man-eating Mohoao! Only Harlan and Kurjak, with the help of a “rangatira”, an old Maori chief, can hope to stop this ancestral threat...
name: La selva della paura

description: In a Boston condo, some tenants are haunted by strange and excruciating dreams, set inside some parts of their own building. In the alleys, on the stairs, inside the basement and the attics, they see monsters and vampires. After a call from the gorgeous Stacy, a psychoanalyst that has one of the tenants as a patient, Harlan rents a flat and soon finds himself dreaming as well… The Dampyr is counting on the help from «amesha» Anyel Zant to prevail over the obscure forces that siege the building. It’s only too late when he realizes the place is a trap nobody can escape from, a place where Boston external reality – Anyel included – doesn’t count anymore for nothing. The thing that’s attacking and invading the building is coming through dreams from a farther and far more alien realm …
name: Prigionieri dei sogni

description: A spate of strange and bloody murders unravels Germany. They all show the same m.o., with an inexplicable trait, though: the perpetrator is always a different person. Involved in this enigma by her disquieting visions, Ann Jurging, with Harlan’s help, tries to trace back the dark origin of this curse — a seductive and hard-to-catch she-devil, called Ghilàn!
name: L'ombra del drago

description:
The (possibly) very best PS-comics by Will Eisner, collected to one book.

But, what is PS (besides postscript)? Well, it`s an educational magazine started in the 50`s, that teaches American (and maybe a few other countries) soldiers, how to keep good care of all kinds of things at the army. The first one to make those comics was Will Eisner. The stories always have humor and exxagerated situations and characters, to make the learning easier, and less tedious.

A way that has been proved to be effective enough, numerously in the past.

description: Greg Irons was a psychedelic poster artist, underground cartoonist, book illustrator, and an emerging tattoo art virtuoso who brought a new sensibility to an age-old art form. This retrospective book spans his whole artistic career, from his earliest dance posters, to his groundbreaking science fiction and horror comix, to his innovative and colorful tattoo art. Greg Irons was one of the elite among poster artists who worked for Bill Graham's Fillmore Ballroom in San Francisco during the Age of Aquarius, designing posters for Chuck Berry, Jefferson Airplane, Big Brother, and Paul Butterfield. You Call This Art?! reprints his finest psychedelic posters in full-color, as well as complete comic stories from Slow Death Funnies, Legions of Charlies, Deviant Slice, Yellow Dog, Thrilling Murder, and many other underground comic books. It also includes rarely seen album cover art for Jerry Garcia, Blue Cheer, Jefferson Starship and other counterculture musicians. Irons has a third career as an illustrator of children's coloring books, and pages from books including One Old Oxford Ox, Last of the Dinosaurs, Pirates, and Wyf of Bathe appear as well. Many examples of his tattoo art are also included. Think you've seen it all already? Not a chance. This book reproduces not only his greatest artistic hits, but also never-before-seen pages from his private sketchbooks and journals, personal photographs, and works that appeared in obscure publications, like the San Francisco Organ, which published the lurid story that Mick Jagger tried to suppress.

description:
Move over, Josie & the Pussycats!

At last, a girl-centered comic book that actually appeals to girls (and even their parents)! Co-created by comics living legends Peter Bagge (Hate) and Gilbert Hernandez (Love and Rockets) on writer and artist duties respectively*, Yeah! is a unique masterpiece of all-ages fun. Originally published as a nine-issue comic book series from 1999-2000 by DC’s Wildstorm imprint, this all-ages gem (approved by the Comics Code Authority, no less!) is collected here for the very first time.

Krazy (vocals and guitars), Honey (drums) and WooWoo (keyboards) are the members of the pop band Yeah! They’ve achieved intergalactic superstardom on every planet but their own (Earth), where they live in anonymity and suffer indignities in their home of suburban New Jersey. The girls struggle with bad gigs (struggling to win $200 amateur-night contests despite playing to packed crowds of adoring fans on Uranus), aliens who have crushes on them, and rival boy band The Snobs.

Fans of Peter Bagge's artwork, don't fret: he breaks out the ol' pencil for a 4-page backup story starring The Snobs (inked by Fantagraphics' own Eric Reynolds). And Love and Rockets fans take note: this comic features perhaps the longest-ever collaboration with Gilbert and his brother Jaime, who inks a whole chapter!
